@title Expiring Multi Party Contract creator.
 @notice Factory contract to create and register new instances of expiring multiparty contracts.
 Responsible for constraining the parameters used to construct a new EMP. This creator contains a number of constraints
 that are applied to newly created expiring multi party contract. These constraints can evolve over time and are
 initially constrained to conservative values in this first iteration. Technically there is nothing in the
 ExpiringMultiParty contract requiring these constraints. However, because `createExpiringMultiParty()` is intended
 to be the only way to create valid financial contracts that are registered with the DVM (via _registerContract),
we can enforce deployment configurations here.

typeDescriptions.typeString: function (string memory,string memory,uint8) external returns (contract ExpandedIERC20)
function (struct ExpiringMultiPartyCreator.Params memory,contract ExpandedIERC20) view returns (struct Liquidatable.ConstructorParams memory)

params._timerAddress: Contract that stores the current time in a testing environment.
params._tokenFactoryAddress: ERC20 token factory used to deploy synthetic token instances.

returns._0: address of the deployed ExpiringMultiParty contract.
uint for the current Testable timestamp.

params.time: timestamp to set current Testable time to.

createExpiringMultiParty((uint256,addres.notice: Creates an instance of expiring multi party and registers it within the registry.

getCurrentTime().notice: Gets the current time. Will return the last time set in `setCurrentTime` if running in test mode. Otherwise, it will return the block timestamp.

userdoc.notice: Factory contract to create and register new instances of expiring multiparty contracts. Responsible for constraining the parameters used to construct a new EMP. This creator contains a number of constraints that are applied to newly created expiring multi party contract. These constraints can evolve over time and are initially constrained to conservative values in this first iteration. Technically there is nothing in the ExpiringMultiParty contract requiring these constraints. However, because `createExpiringMultiParty()` is intended to be the only way to create valid financial contracts that are registered with the DVM (via _registerContract), we can enforce deployment configurations here.
